In this case, `unimplemented!` acts as an attribute macro that expects arguments on its own line or within a block. You can't pass arguments directly to the function itself; you need them inside the macro definition for the compiler to know what to expect.

This is actually a pattern common in large codebases where you need to defer logic until runtime.

